<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1055298-is-it-for-10-and-up">Is it for 10 and up?</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1055298'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F1289617.The_Forgotten_Man">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1055298-is-it-for-10-and-up">4 years ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1055298-is-it-for-10-and-up">See all 2 answers</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/92990053-maureen-brown"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1549057553i/92990053._UX100_CR0,0,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/92990053-maureen-brown">Maureen Brown</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">To hell with sophisticated readers. My mother, who died at age 90, three years ago (with military honors--she was one of the last of WWII women vetera<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">To hell with sophisticated readers. My mother, who died at age 90, three years ago (with military honors--she was one of the last of WWII women veterans) was both a reader and a writer, and selling books became my later life's profession just to keep her in books. She read histories and biographies mostly, but would read whatever was on hand if she had nothing else, such as nursing manuals, agricultural reports, travel books--anything non-fiction (she stopped reading fiction in her sixties unless it was really exceptional), and she exhausted the libraries of every town she ever lived in. She told me when I was just a pup that she believed in freedom of speech for ALL, including children, and that I was allowed to read anything I was capable of reading and was interested in. Period. (I still read "Peyton Place" in secret when I was ten, up in my "treehouse," an old door across two limbs of a sycamore tree, not because I wasn't allowed, but because I was still ashamed, as "backwards" Kentuckians were then). Nothing I ever read lessened me by reading it; on the contrary, it added to the totality of who I am. I taught my daughter and grandsons that same thing. FREE SPEECH FOR ALL<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerFooter'>

<div class='flagAnswer'>
<a class="right flag" rel="nofollow" id="flag_link827229" title="Flag this answer as inappropriate." href="/flagged/new?resource_id=827229&amp;resource_type=CommunityAnswer&amp;return_url=%2Fquestions%2F1055298-is-it-for-10-and-up%2Fanswers%2F827229-to-hell-with">flag</a>
</div>
